Green Deal: Only two sign-up despite £1,000 cashback The Government’s flagship Green Deal scheme, aimed at encouraging households to become more energy efficient, looks set for an uncertain launch next week. By Kara Gammell
10:42AM GMT 22 Jan 2013
Follow Comments
The initiative aims to get loans to households so they can invest in energy efficiency measures, such as boiler upgrades, wall or loft insulation or double-glazing windows. The cost of borrowing the money should be more than covered through reduced energy use, with repayments made through your electricity bill. There is also potential to get financial assistance to install energy generators such as solar panels and wind turbines. However, mortgage experts are advising caution because any loan from the scheme would be attached to the property, rather than the individual, and could create complications if they choose to sell. And with only nine days to go until the launch on January 28 – when improvement works can begin – the Department of Energy & Climate Change (DECC) has not published any calculations or projections on how much can be saved or how long it will take to pay the debt off if you adopt the various energy-efficiency measures. Critics have questioned the reliability of the savings. It has been suggested that a large number of homes in Britain are currently under-heated, so energy-efficient measures such as insulation may not result in the savings expected because households will use the same amount of energy but have warmer properties. Related Articles
